title: For Sale/Trade:  Hungarian AK-47 AKM AKMS Collapsible Underfolder Folding Stock and 1000 rds. 7.62x39 7.62mm Tula Ammo
postcontent: For sale or trade is an underfolding Hungarian AK-47 (or more accurately, an AKMS).  Professionally built from a hand-picked, all-numbers-matching, unissued parts kit on a NoDak Spud receiver.  Numbers match all the way to the dust cover.  (Not actually made by Saiga, but I didn't want this mixed in with the 'Norinco's and 'Century's) Has the original chrome-lined, Communist-made hammer forged barrel that are getting so hard to find these days; condition of the barrel is absolutely perfect.  Rifle was Duracoated, but there are some honest wear marks and scuffs on some of the 'high traffic' areas.  I'm not going to lie and claim that it's a tack-driver, but it is honestly the most accurate AK I've ever handled: plinking from the standing position gave a group within the size of a soda can at 75'; someone with a little more skill should be able to do very respectably with this rifle.  Stock locks up nice and tight in open and closed position; some minor wobble when open, but it's an easy fix.  Includes four 30-round magazines, magazine pouch, drop bag, and front sight adjustment tool (not that it needs it).  In addition, I'll be throwing in 1000 (Okay, 995) rounds of Tula 7.62x39mm ammo to get you started.

title: For Trade:  S&W Model 10 .38 Special Revolver (K Frame)
location: Souuth Side 55th & Seneca Area, Wichita, Kansas
postcontent:
The S&W Model 10 was made to shoot.  
They are just super accurate, with an awesome trigger and great lock up.
They were favored by law enforcement for 
	1. they have a great balance and feel. 
	2. They are easy to qualify with and 
	3. they are easy to carry and handle.  
The trigger in single action is made for target shooting, but the Double Action pull is what I really like on this gun. It stages  well and the drop of the hammer is just right for good D.A. control. 
I  carry this gun all the time and the high ride holster with just a standard T-Shirt. The holster is all leather and custom fit just for this gun. It is thin leather and it is easy to wear and conceal.

title: For Sale:  First Aid/Survival Course Taught by an Active Duty Navy SEAL
location: South of Ashland, Ohio, United States
postcontent:
Basic First Aid/TCCC Course 

Taught By an active duty Navy SEAL Medic 

Learn procedures that could save your life or that life of someone you love in one day. Learn the advanced medical procedures that are taught to today’s modern Special Operation Forces (SOF) including the Navy SEALs, SWCC, the Army’s Green Beret and Army Rangers, 160th SOAR and Marine Force Recon. These methods have been learned though out the past 13 years of fighting and are proven to work and are tried and true methods of advanced lifesaving medical care.  

Date/Time: Saturday, July 20th/9:00 AM- around 4:00 PM (I will be willing to stay later) 

Price: $125/person for standard classes (discounts available; see below) 

Class Size Limit:  10 

If you would like I can prove that I am an active duty Navy SEAL and provide copies of all of my credentials and certifications. I would be more than happy to prove that I am a real SEAL and not one of the many “fakes” out there. I would be more than happy to give you my class number and answer any and all questions to the best of my ability and even provide you with the answer as to whether or not your buddy or acquaintances down the street, who claims to have been a SEAL, is for real or is one of those “fakes”. 

Do you know what to do when someone you love is hurt and needs medical attention right away? This Basic First Aid Course will teach you the principles of TCCC and what you need to do when 911 is just too far away to provide help. 

A LITTLE ABOUT ME: 
Here is a little background on me. I am an active duty Navy SEAL. One of my specialties in the SEAL Teams is being the platoon medic. Some of the schools I have attended that are medical related included the Joint Special Operations Medical Training Center located at Fort Bragg, NC where I attended 13 months of medical training. During my time there I completed training in Combat Trauma Management, Advance Trauma Management, Advance Trauma Practitioner, Trauma Patient Assessment, TCCC, CPR, PEPP, Anatomy and Physiology, Pharmacology, Trauma I, II, and III. I also have attended SOT training in California. My medical qualifications include the following: EMT, BLS, ACLS, Special Operations Combat Medic, active duty Navy SEAL platoon medic, and being a Dive Medical Technician. I have worked in a number of different medical capacities including Tampa General Hospital in their Emergency Department, OR, Burn Intensive Care Unit, Nero ICU, Post-Op ICU, maternity ward, and their life flight. I have also worked on Tampa Fire Rescue responding to calls on their Advance Life Support rigs. I have deployed as the only medic for a SEAL platoon to countries where the most advance medical care and resources were what I carried on my back. I don't pretend to know it all....far from it. That is why I constantly have to be studying and trying to further myself but I can teach you how to provide first aid to yourself and your family that will work and is easy to understand. I am a small town country boy myself so I know how to make things understandable for those who do not have a prior medical background. I am sure you will not have a problem keeping up with the information. I enjoy medicine and I enjoy teaching others about it. I look forward to being able to help you better prepare yourself and your family for those emergency situations that we all hope will never happen but unfortunately do at any time. 




COURSE DESCRIPTION: 
This first aid course is geared towards the young and the old, the hunter, those how like hiking and the outdoors, the husband or father, wife or mother, or any individual who wants to know how to provide basic first aid to themselves, their family, friends, or the stranger on the street who just got in an accident. Do you know what to do if and when disaster strikes? You will be better prepared if you attend my Basic First Aid Course. There is no need for any prior medical knowledge as I know how to take all the medical “mumble jumble” talk and make is simple and easy to understand. This course, although basic, I will guarantee, will set you up for success in the event you or someone you know needs lifesaving interventions and 911 is going to take to long to arrive. Now I am do not intend to be able to make everyone who attends my course a paramedic or EMT. I am not saying you shouldn't call 911...of course you should, but sometimes you might find yourself in a remote, dangerous area and help is to far away. The facts are that if someone has massive hemorrhaging they can bleed out and die within 60-90 seconds....that isn't very long. I have set this course up in the same format that I teach my fellow Navy SEALs. It is based around a simple and easy to follow format. It has to be, we are expected to follow it while getting shot at. This is the important stuff you really need to know and really can't afford to do without. Now, before I go on I just want to be very clear that this course will not make you certified in CPR, BLS, ACLS, or any other form of life support. From a legal stand point I am not making you qualified to go out and preform any form of first aid to anyone. This course is for a group of people who personally want to learn the real hands on aspects of first aid and be able to know what to do one of your family members or yourself is in harm’s way. Bluntly put, you can either stand by and watch as they die or you can intervene and help and possibly save their life....this course will teach you how to increase their chances of survival but the choice of action is still yours....  

Topics to be covered in the Basic First Aid Course include: 
MARCH (the new move advanced ABCs) 
Pressure Points 
Pressure Bandages 
How to stop non-compressible bleeding 
Tourniquets: How and when to use them and proper placement and application (there is a little more to it than you might think) 
Improvised Tourniquets 
Hemostatic Agents 
Amputations 
Establishing Airways/Clearing Airways 
Advance Airways that are simply and lifesaving that even doctors don't do...more on that in the class 
Improvised Airways 
Breathing for a patient 
Chest seals 
Improvised Chest seals 
Needle Decompressions: How, when and where 
Fluid Replacement 
The major effect of Hypothermia and how to prevent it in different types of patients 
Patient surveys 
How to approach a trauma patient 
Blood sweeps 
Primary Surveys 
Secondary Surveys 
Maintaining a Patient 
Splinting 
C spine stabilization: How and when 
Improvised C collars 
Burns 
Crush Injury 
Working with an assistant 
Working by yourself 
First aid kits: What you should carry; what works and what doesn't 
Tactical Medic 
All types of buddy carries 
CPR (I save this for last to clarify that although we will cover it and talk about it, you will not be certified in CPR when you complete this course although you will understand how to do it) 

As you can see that is a lot to cover in a day. Just one last time; notice that nowhere in that list is there a certification in for any profession or any sort of professional qualification. That isn't the purpose of this course. If you want to be certified in CPR which is always a good step and I would suggest the American Red Cross for certification. I will present and teach the material all Special Operation Forces in the US military learn from the Navy SEALs to the Army Rangers to the Green Berets. Not really a "basic" course but yet it is easy for everyone to follow and understand. As I have said, there is no need for prior medical experience but it never hurts. You will not find all the stuff you get from this one course anywhere else and learn all that you will in just one day. Also, you will have an opportunity to purchase first aid supplies directly from me at a discounted price. As for what you need to bring it isn't much. You will need the remaining payment due at the beginning of the course first thing in the morning. Payment is explained below.  
Also, bring water, sun screen and such. If you have any first aid equipment or supplies that you would like to train with you can bring them but it isn't necessary. 
Lunch will be provided for free and could be anything from a home cooked meal prepared by my wife (and she is an excellent cook as she has attended a few culinary schools in her time) to a BBQ also completely furnished by me. However, if you have any food allergies, or if you would prefer to bring your own lunch that is 100% acceptable just please let me know which you would like to do before the day of the class. If you want to have a good time, learn about Basic First Aid so you are better prepared when disaster happens, come join us and make new friends!  
CONTACT:  You can contact me to register for the next upcoming course at idblab@live.com or text or call 757-319-1709.  
PRICING:  $125 per person for group sessions (family discounts and military discounts available for 10%); $250 per household for private courses of instruction (contact me to work out the details) 
20% non-refundable deposit is required at the time of registering for the class; this deposit is only refundable in case of a weather day (see below); the rest of the amount due will be paid on the day of the class before we begin 
PAYMENT METHODS:  Cash, Personal Check, Money Order, Cashier’s Check, Silver, Guns, Trade/Barter, I am pretty open to this sort of thing and I am willing to pay you if the item you have to exchange is more valuable; let's see what you got and what we can work out 
CLASS SIZE LIMIT:   10 People 
WEATHER DAYS:   Since some of the hands on stuff takes more room for a group classes will generally be conducted outside. Weather permitting the classes will be held on the scheduled day. All deposits will be returned if we are rained out. Private classes should be able to be conducted inside if desired and could still take place. 
LOCATION:   Two miles South of Ashland

For those who aren’t up to speed, here you go: The XDm is the latest of the polymer-frame, striker-fired pistols, and it corrects some earlier designs, both Springfield’s and those of competitors. The angled slide is both easier to pack comfortably and easier to work, as the slide serrations grab back when you get a hold of them.

It is accurate due to the match-dimensioned chamber and bore and the snug, but not excessively tight fit of barrel to slide. Fully hardened, the barrel is not going to wear to a sloppy fit with less than a lifetime’s worth of ammo. Also, the barrel will not throw a hissy fit if you happen to use or load ammo containing lead bullets.

The magazines hold more rounds than comparable polymer-frame pistols. The full-size XDm in .40 holds 16+1 rounds..
